snippet.textDisplay: One other thing I think you missed. I think rich and poor people both have some sense that the economy isn't fair, but poor people feel like they can't fix it and rich people like to convince themselves that they're not part of the problem even if they hold onto their own wealth and don't do anything to help the less fortunate. So this guy who goes out and does something about the problem and who might or might not be a nobleman himself resonates with everyone but the least self-aware of social darwinists, and even they find this strong protagonist who achieves things relatable.

snippet.textDisplay: I have a suggestion for Blue's travel bucket list: Nimes, France. I visited there today and it has some of the best preserved Roman architecture in the world. Their arena is still in use (mostly bull fighting, but also some historical reenactment), though apparently there had been a small settlement built inside of it for a few centuries. There is also a temple dedicated to the imperial family that is so well preserved that it looks more like a 19th reproduction than a 2000 year old building...no dome though...sorry.

snippet.textDisplay: My two favorite versions of Robin Hood have to be the Disney version where he's a fox..as the whole roguish clever thief thing really meshes well with all the legends about foxes over the years, and the Archer class Heroic Spirit Robin Hood from the Fate universe of Type Moon as he's not just 1 single Robin Hood but more an amalgam of different legends of the man with this particular version being the son of a wandering druid who was treated as an outcast as he was thought to be possessed by fairies. There's a lot more to the story but you'd have to go to the Type Moon wiki for it..it's rather lengthy, still a good adaptation of the myth.

snippet.textDisplay: I protest against your usage of dragons as a symbol for capitalists. A dragon is pretty much as anti-capitalist as it gets: it takes money away from the rich and deny them to everyone equally, thus shutting down one of the very roots of the capitalist system: goods-money exchange. And kobolds that are usually led by dragons are as communist as it gets.

snippet.textDisplay:
I like to think of Robin Hood as a cautionary tale for those in power about how the whole “Divine Right of Kings” thing is actually supposed to work. Something along the lines of, “Yeah, God gave you fabulous wealth and immense power, but those things come with the responsibility to care for and protect those below you. And if you fail to live up to the responsibilities that power and wealth entail, God might just be displeased enough to knock you down a peg or two.”

Basically, Karmic Retribution in form-fitting leggings.

EDIT: Also, I kinda want to see a version of the story portraying the Sheriff in a different light. Less “Snidely Whiplash” and more “Good and Honorable Man bound by his oaths/personal moral compass/etc. to serve a Villain unworthy of his loyalty”. I’m honestly surprised that nobody’s done something like this before.

snippet.textDisplay:
Even more than Robin Hood being a writer's wet dream, imo the big popularity he always had should be connected to the figure he is behind all the usual stories.

He is a good guy who happens to be quite the jerk when needed but that stands against an Evil Authority and helps the poor/does what those poors would like to do themselves.
He is simply an image of the "Sticking It to the man yo", and that can't go ignored in our industrial world.

Just imagine being a worker in some factory in the late 1800/early 1900 UK/US.
You are EXACTLY the kind of person Robin Hood would have supported if you lived 700/800 years before. It's hard to not like him.
